WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:05.260
&gt;&gt; From the library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:06.350 --> 00:00:10.210
&gt;&gt; Now for what we are really all
here for, Holly Robinson Peete.

00:00:10.210 --> 00:00:11.910
I'm so excited.

00:00:11.910 --> 00:00:15.430
She is a force and a
woman of many talents.

00:00:15.430 --> 00:00:17.860
Of course, we all know
her as an actress,

00:00:17.860 --> 00:00:20.480
a singer, an author, of course.

00:00:20.480 --> 00:00:23.980
She has been in the entertainment
industry for most of her life

00:00:23.980 --> 00:00:27.870
and found success in hit movies
and shows like 21 Jump Street,

00:00:27.870 --> 00:00:29.450
and of course, my personal
favorites,

00:00:29.450 --> 00:00:32.550
Hanging with Mr. Cooper
and For Your Love.

00:00:32.550 --> 00:00:36.440
But there are a few other talents
that she touts on her Instagram

00:00:36.440 --> 00:00:39.320
and I think we should, they're
really highly important.

00:00:39.320 --> 00:00:44.110
First, mom of four, of course,
she is a resolution seeker,

00:00:44.110 --> 00:00:46.410
a philanthropist, and then a few

00:00:46.410 --> 00:00:49.490
that I don't think we
know too much about.

00:00:49.490 --> 00:00:54.250
Plumber, Uber driver,
and dog interpreter.

00:00:54.250 --> 00:00:57.950
And I guess as a mom of four
you do what must be done.

00:00:57.950 --> 00:00:59.980
And she's doing what must be done.

00:00:59.980 --> 00:01:01.830
Her philanthropic efforts
through her

00:01:01.830 --> 00:01:05.690
and her husband's organization
Holly Rod Foundation have won,

00:01:05.690 --> 00:01:09.140
not only won awards for
compassionate service,

00:01:09.140 --> 00:01:13.160 position:56%
but have placed a national spotlight
on two causes very personal

00:01:13.160 --> 00:01:17.080
to the Peete family,
Parkinson's disease and Autism.

00:01:17.080 --> 00:01:20.310
Holly Robinson Peete is
an award winning author

00:01:20.310 --> 00:01:24.910
and has won an NAACP Image Award
for her outstanding literary work

00:01:24.910 --> 00:01:29.410
in her children's book entitled
My Brother Charlie about autism

00:01:29.410 --> 00:01:32.040
from the sibling's
perspective co-authored

00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:34.710
by her daughter Ryan
Elizabeth Peete.

00:01:34.710 --> 00:01:37.820
Her latest book Same
But Different Teen Life

00:01:37.820 --> 00:01:42.300
on the Autism Express paints an
important story of hope for teens

00:01:42.300 --> 00:01:45.580
and families living with
autism, and lets us all see

00:01:45.580 --> 00:01:49.820
that everybody's unique
rhythm is worth dancing to.

00:01:49.820 --> 00:01:54.450
The book was co-written with her
twin children Ryan Elizabeth Peete

00:01:54.450 --> 00:01:56.830
and R.J Tweet Peete
who was diagnosed

00:01:56.830 --> 00:01:58.990
with autism at the age of three.

00:01:58.990 --> 00:02:02.480
Holly Robinson Peete continues
to do what must be done and more

00:02:02.480 --> 00:02:07.130 position:56%
to inspire teens and families living
with autism, and we appreciate her

00:02:07.130 --> 00:02:11.430
and her family for being a symbol
of hope and light for us all.

00:02:11.430 --> 00:02:16.030
So without further ado, please help
me welcome Holly Robinson Peete.

00:02:16.030 --> 00:02:26.140
[ Applause ]

00:02:26.140 --> 00:02:27.440
&gt;&gt; Thank you so much.

00:02:27.440 --> 00:02:29.230
What a great introduction.

00:02:29.230 --> 00:02:30.740
Can you come back home
with me to L.A.

00:02:30.740 --> 00:02:32.700
and just introduce me
like that every morning?

00:02:32.700 --> 00:02:34.000
[ Laughter ]

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:35.890
&gt;&gt; Can you imagine if
you woke up every morning

00:02:35.890 --> 00:02:38.060
and you were introduced
like that to your kids?

00:02:38.060 --> 00:02:39.360
[ Laughter ]

00:02:39.360 --> 00:02:40.660
&gt;&gt; That'd be fabulous.

00:02:40.660 --> 00:02:43.340
I am-let me find my clicker.

00:02:43.340 --> 00:02:46.600
Wala. I am so excited
to be here today.

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:48.140
What an amazing festival.

00:02:48.140 --> 00:02:51.700
It's my first time here
and I absolutely love it.

00:02:51.700 --> 00:02:56.100
Thank you to all of you who
came to this presentation today.

00:02:56.100 --> 00:02:59.230
As many of you know, if
you didn't know before,

00:02:59.230 --> 00:03:02.180
you know I am a mom
first, a mom of four,

00:03:02.180 --> 00:03:04.580 position:56%
and I have a son with special needs.

00:03:04.580 --> 00:03:07.000
And it's been pretty
much the narrative

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.570
of my life for the last 18 years.

00:03:10.570 --> 00:03:14.860
And there's nothing more fulfilling
than when you have a situation

00:03:14.860 --> 00:03:17.740
that happens to you that
can be quite devastating

00:03:17.740 --> 00:03:20.570
and then you're able to
eventually see it as a blessing

00:03:20.570 --> 00:03:22.410 position:56%
because you're able to touch others.

00:03:22.410 --> 00:03:24.550
It's a really tremendous feeling.

00:03:24.550 --> 00:03:27.880
So, I'm just absolutely
thrilled to be able to be here

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:29.800
and share my story with you.

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:32.510
Oh, OK. So, it works.

00:03:32.510 --> 00:03:34.060
Ya'll, you're listening that's
the first thing you're just

00:03:34.060 --> 00:03:35.360
so excited that the clicker works.

00:03:35.360 --> 00:03:36.660
[ Laughter ]

00:03:36.660 --> 00:03:39.020
&gt;&gt; So, My Brother-we're
going to talk about Same

00:03:39.020 --> 00:03:40.460
But Different, which
is our new book.

00:03:40.460 --> 00:03:42.650
My Brother Charlie is a
book I'm super proud of.

00:03:42.650 --> 00:03:46.500
I came to Scholastic many years
ago, and I pitched this book.

00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:50.990
And I went to several publishers,
and they really didn't get it.

00:03:50.990 --> 00:03:56.070
They really didn't get the
pervasive, prevalence of autism

00:03:56.070 --> 00:03:57.420
and they just didn't understand.

00:03:57.420 --> 00:03:59.880
And certainly in communities
of color

00:03:59.880 --> 00:04:02.000
where our children our
diagnosed two to five years later

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:05.320
than other children, it was really
important to have a book like this,

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:07.670
especially from the
sibling's perspective.

00:04:07.670 --> 00:04:09.690
And so these are my twins.

00:04:09.690 --> 00:04:14.010
Aww, yeah, they're-- they're
18, so the aww factor is gone.

00:04:14.010 --> 00:04:15.880
[ Laughter ]

00:04:15.880 --> 00:04:22.100
Aww. But back then, it was
aww, so cute, born in '97.

00:04:22.100 --> 00:04:23.400
This is my dad.

00:04:23.400 --> 00:04:26.270 position:56%
So many of you of a certain age will
remember my dad was the original

00:04:26.270 --> 00:04:27.570
Gordon on Sesame Street.

00:04:27.570 --> 00:04:28.870
[ Cheering ]

00:04:28.870 --> 00:04:30.170
Yeah.

00:04:30.170 --> 00:04:31.470
[ Applause ]

00:04:31.470 --> 00:04:34.030
He is my inspiration for reading,

00:04:34.030 --> 00:04:37.240
for-I mean the man could tell a
story like you couldn't imagine,

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:40.360
and he wrote so many stories
as Gordon on Sesame Street.

00:04:40.360 --> 00:04:41.660
He was the original Gordon.

00:04:41.660 --> 00:04:44.320
So that was like '69 to '72.

00:04:44.320 --> 00:04:49.140
And he was an amazing man, awesome
writer, wrote for everything

00:04:49.140 --> 00:04:52.900
from Sanford and Son, The
Cosby Show, the Waltons.

00:04:52.900 --> 00:04:57.850 position:56%
I mean he's a guy who really had a
lot to contribute to this television

00:04:57.850 --> 00:05:03.970 position:56%
and entertainment, but was diagnosed
with Parkinson's disease at only 45.

00:05:03.970 --> 00:05:06.680
Yeah, it was deep because
it was in the 80's.

00:05:06.680 --> 00:05:08.790
And I was just a freshman
in college,

00:05:08.790 --> 00:05:13.230 position:56%
and I didn't know what Parkinson's
was, and we didn't have the internet

00:05:13.230 --> 00:05:14.930
and Google yet and
you know Mohammed Ali.

00:05:14.930 --> 00:05:18.310
We just didn't have a whole lot
and it was kind of a scary time.

00:05:18.310 --> 00:05:21.220
But through him it led
me to a life of service.

00:05:21.220 --> 00:05:24.450
And then through our books we
were able to serve even more.

00:05:24.450 --> 00:05:27.370
So, here's some more cute
pictures of the twins.

00:05:27.370 --> 00:05:29.430
Oh, I love this picture
because you can tell

00:05:29.430 --> 00:05:31.520
when R.J. was just
diagnosed around this time,

00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:33.380
Ryan was really there for him.

00:05:33.380 --> 00:05:35.690
You know, she always turned
his frown upside down,

00:05:35.690 --> 00:05:36.990
like we used to say.

00:05:36.990 --> 00:05:38.650
And she's always had his back.

00:05:38.650 --> 00:05:41.430
We got our diagnosis in 1999.

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:44.960
We call it the never day because
we were told he was never going

00:05:44.960 --> 00:05:46.670
to be so many things.

00:05:46.670 --> 00:05:50.850
This pediatrician just
basically, bless her heart,

00:05:50.850 --> 00:05:52.520
decided she was going to
give us a laundry list

00:05:52.520 --> 00:05:55.090
of what he would never
do at three years old.

00:05:55.090 --> 00:05:59.200
So, it's very, you know, it comes
with a lot of audacity to be able

00:05:59.200 --> 00:06:02.500
to tell a parent that your
kid will never say I love you,

00:06:02.500 --> 00:06:06.250
never do a whole bunch of things
that he eventually ended up doing.

00:06:06.250 --> 00:06:10.820
So, I want to quickly play this
little quick video that Ryan,

00:06:10.820 --> 00:06:14.460
his twin sister, and his
little brothers made.

00:06:14.460 --> 00:06:17.530
So, that's why it's a
little bit, it looks young.

00:06:17.530 --> 00:06:19.620
It's not professional.

00:06:19.620 --> 00:06:25.510
But it just gives a very good first
person narrative of who R.J. is.

00:06:25.510 --> 00:06:30.470
[ Music ]

00:06:30.470 --> 00:06:32.360
&gt;&gt; My name is Rodney Jackson Peete.

