00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:05.910
I'm so proud of her.

00:08:05.910 --> 00:08:10.320
My mom and I wrote
a song about autism.

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:11.620
Wanna hear it?

00:08:11.620 --> 00:08:17.010
I may have autism, but
autism doesn't have me.

00:08:17.010 --> 00:08:18.310
[ Applause ]

00:08:18.310 --> 00:08:19.610
&gt;&gt; So, that's R.J.

00:08:19.610 --> 00:08:20.910
[ Applause ]

00:08:20.910 --> 00:08:25.430
So that's R.J. and you
can see he's a sweet kid,

00:08:25.430 --> 00:08:27.500
and he didn't have
language for so long.

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:31.060
And we really wanted to use his
example to give other people hope.

00:08:31.060 --> 00:08:34.020 position:56%
Because that's really what we didn't
have when we got our diagnosis.

00:08:34.020 --> 00:08:37.970
We wrote this book for many
reasons, very obvious reasons being

00:08:37.970 --> 00:08:41.060
that autism is very
prevalent right now,

00:08:41.060 --> 00:08:44.850
and wanted to promote awareness.

00:08:44.850 --> 00:08:47.530
But in the end, it
was really about hope.

00:08:47.530 --> 00:08:51.830
It was really about peddling
hope, making sure that people

00:08:51.830 --> 00:08:54.270
that were given the diagnosis
that we were given can know

00:08:54.270 --> 00:08:57.470
that our kids can eventually
become part of society

00:08:57.470 --> 00:08:59.380
and be loved and have talents.

00:08:59.380 --> 00:09:01.080
And we're always talking
about what they can't do,

00:09:01.080 --> 00:09:03.440
but we wanted to show
what they can do.

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:06.990
So, one of the reasons
that we started,

00:09:06.990 --> 00:09:11.390
I started becoming an author is
because I went to school one day

00:09:11.390 --> 00:09:14.410 position:56%
and my daughter Ryan said, "No one
knows at school what autism is, Mom.

00:09:14.410 --> 00:09:16.870
So, we got to tell them,
because no one knows."

00:09:16.870 --> 00:09:18.870
This was like third
grade or fourth grade.

00:09:18.870 --> 00:09:21.810
And so, I said, "Well, Dad and
I we'll go down to the school

00:09:21.810 --> 00:09:23.110
and have a conversation."

00:09:23.110 --> 00:09:24.570
She was like, "That's OK.

00:09:24.570 --> 00:09:27.080
We don't need you to
go down to school."

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:29.150
[ Laughter ]

00:09:29.150 --> 00:09:32.670
[laughter] So, I said, "No, Ryan,
you have to understand like we need

00:09:32.670 --> 00:09:34.120
to come down there and
have a conversation.

00:09:34.120 --> 00:09:35.470
You don't have to be
in the classroom,

00:09:35.470 --> 00:09:36.860
but we need to explain it."

00:09:36.860 --> 00:09:41.270 position:56%
And so she gave us the bullet points
on what to say and what not to say.

00:09:41.270 --> 00:09:43.440
She said, obviously,
don't embarrass us.

00:09:43.440 --> 00:09:45.350
She said, make it a
level playing field

00:09:45.350 --> 00:09:48.840
and accentuate the
positive, a sense of humor.

00:09:48.840 --> 00:09:51.000
You know, the first thing
that we said to this group

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:54.450
of fourth graders was, what do you
do well, what don't you do well?

00:09:54.450 --> 00:09:57.200
And one kid was like, "I
really play football well.

00:09:57.200 --> 00:09:58.910
But I don't read good."

00:09:58.910 --> 00:10:01.070
And another kid said you
know, "I'm great at math.

00:10:01.070 --> 00:10:02.370
But I don't know how
to play soccer."

00:10:02.370 --> 00:10:04.230
And I said, "Well, R.J.
can tell you the names

00:10:04.230 --> 00:10:06.520
of every single president
and vice president.

00:10:06.520 --> 00:10:08.810
He can tell you the name
of every single player

00:10:08.810 --> 00:10:11.810
on every sport league that exists.

00:10:11.810 --> 00:10:14.080
But he has a hard time
making friends."

00:10:14.080 --> 00:10:16.790
And it was amazing, like this
fog just lifted over them,

00:10:16.790 --> 00:10:18.740
and it was pretty awesome.

00:10:18.740 --> 00:10:23.190
Autism in America is out
of control quite frankly.

00:10:23.190 --> 00:10:26.910
There are so many kids
diagnosed with this disorder.

00:10:26.910 --> 00:10:28.210
It's very mysterious.

00:10:28.210 --> 00:10:31.410
We didn't know about it
until we were impacted by it.

00:10:31.410 --> 00:10:34.920
And the more we talk about it,
the more we write books about it,

00:10:34.920 --> 00:10:37.280
the more the stigma goes away.

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:40.730
And that's another goal of ours.

00:10:40.730 --> 00:10:43.940
Just, these are-now
R.J. is growing up now.

00:10:43.940 --> 00:10:47.390
He's getting hair on his
face, and, yeah mommy's trying

00:10:47.390 --> 00:10:49.010
to cut it while he's sleeping.

00:10:49.010 --> 00:10:50.310
[ Laughter ]

00:10:50.310 --> 00:10:51.610
Trying to shave him.

00:10:51.610 --> 00:10:53.570
I really do try and shave him
while he's sleeping cause.

00:10:53.570 --> 00:10:55.220
And he's just been awesome.

00:10:55.220 --> 00:10:59.010
So we decided we would do a
reality show because why not?

00:10:59.010 --> 00:11:00.310
[ Applause ]

00:11:00.310 --> 00:11:01.610
Because

00:11:01.610 --> 00:11:02.910
[ Applause ]

00:11:02.910 --> 00:11:05.440
So when I pitched this reality
show to my family, I said,

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:09.590
"It's not going to be like-don't
worry there won't be anybody

00:11:09.590 --> 00:11:11.110
throwing drinks in anyone's face.

00:11:11.110 --> 00:11:12.670
And there's no fights.

00:11:12.670 --> 00:11:17.120
But I felt like just like with our
books and going on different shows,

00:11:17.120 --> 00:11:19.900
I wanted to continue the narrative.

00:11:19.900 --> 00:11:22.930
And I felt like it would be really
helpful for people to see us

00:11:22.930 --> 00:11:25.380
in our lives and how
we rally around R.J.,

00:11:25.380 --> 00:11:28.870
and just you know,
we're married 21 years.

00:11:28.870 --> 00:11:31.340
We're not a perfect family at all.

00:11:31.340 --> 00:11:36.540
But we felt like it would be
interesting to show our journey.

00:11:36.540 --> 00:11:40.540 position:56%
And so we're in our-we're about to
start our second season in February.

00:11:40.540 --> 00:11:43.300
We're on the Oprah Winfrey Network.

00:11:43.300 --> 00:11:44.680
The show's called For Peete's Sake.

00:11:44.680 --> 00:11:46.590
And I just bought a couple clips.

00:11:46.590 --> 00:11:49.060
And this just is really,
you know, obviously,

00:11:49.060 --> 00:11:51.630
we're here at a book fest, this
is not a television convention,

00:11:51.630 --> 00:11:55.130
but I wanted to share a couple
of clips because I wanted you

00:11:55.130 --> 00:11:59.940
to see sort of, this is an
extension of our work as authors.

00:11:59.940 --> 00:12:03.450
&gt;&gt; When R.J. and I were three years
old and he was first diagnosed

00:12:03.450 --> 00:12:06.410
with autism, he was having a
lot of trouble communicating.

00:12:06.410 --> 00:12:10.730
I'd almost be his voice and I'd
often speak for him at times.

00:12:10.730 --> 00:12:12.480
I've always been in R.J.'s corner.

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:13.780
&gt;&gt; Go to U.S.C.

00:12:13.780 --> 00:12:15.080
&gt;&gt; You want me to go to U.S.C.?

00:12:15.080 --> 00:12:16.720 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Yeah go to your dad's old school.

00:12:16.720 --> 00:12:19.630
&gt;&gt; Whatever she wants to do, I'll
go with it, and I'll support her.

00:12:19.630 --> 00:12:22.510
But, I want her to go to U.S.C.
so she's close to me a lot.

00:12:22.510 --> 00:12:26.240
[ Music ]

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:28.210
&gt;&gt; Well, she went to N.Y.U.
She didn't go to U.S.C.

00:12:28.210 --> 00:12:30.400
[ Laughter ]

